{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01VnpPfG9pdyN44uTwUYoFwe","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# ezpdf\n     2→\n     3→A fast, lossless PDF manipulation CLI tool written in Rust. Merge, split, remove, rotate, and reorder pages without ever re-encoding content — what goes in comes out at exactly the same quality.\n     4→\n     5→Built as a modern replacement for `pdftk`, with a developer-first experience: clean subcommands, intuitive flags, shell completions, and man pages.\n     6→\n     7→---\n     8→\n     9→## Features\n    10→\n    11→| Command    | Description                                          |\n    12→|------------|------------------------------------------------------|\n    13→| `merge`    | Combine two or more PDFs into one                    |\n    14→| `split`    | Extract a page range or burst into individual pages  |\n    15→| `remove`   | Delete specific pages or ranges                      |\n    16→| `rotate`   | Rotate all or specific pages by 90/180/270°          |\n    17→| `reorder`  | Rearrange pages by specifying a new order            |\n    18→\n    19→---\n    20→\n    21→## Installation\n    22→\n    23→```bash\n    24→# Homebrew (macOS / Linux)\n    25→brew install zhou-en/tap/ezpdf\n    26→\n    27→# Cargo\n    28→cargo install ezpdf\n    29→```\n    30→\n    31→---\n    32→\n    33→## Usage\n    34→\n    35→```bash\n    36→# Merge PDFs\n    37→ezpdf merge a.pdf b.pdf c.pdf -o combined.pdf\n    38→\n    39→# Split — extract a range\n    40→ezpdf split report.pdf 1-10 -o part1.pdf\n    41→\n    42→# Split — burst into individual pages\n    43→ezpdf split report.pdf --each -o ./pages/\n    44→\n    45→# Remove pages\n    46→ezpdf remove report.pdf 3,5,7-9 -o cleaned.pdf\n    47→\n    48→# Rotate all pages\n    49→ezpdf rotate report.pdf 90 -o rotated.pdf\n    50→\n    51→# Rotate specific pages\n    52→ezpdf rotate report.pdf 90 --pages 1,3,5 -o rotated.pdf\n    53→\n    54→# Reorder pages\n    55→ezpdf reorder report.pdf 3,1,2,4 -o reordered.pdf\n    56→\n    57→# Shell completions\n    58→ezpdf completions zsh >> ~/.zshrc\n    59→```\n    60→\n    61→Page ranges use `1-5,7,9-12` syntax consistently across all commands. Pages are 1-indexed.\n    62→\n    63→---\n    64→\n    65→## Architecture\n    66→\n    67→### Workspace Structure\n    68→\n    69→`ezpdf` is a Cargo workspace with a shared core library. All PDF logic lives in `ezpdf-core` — the CLI and the future desktop app are thin shells over it.\n    70→\n    71→```mermaid\n    72→%% Architecture: Cargo workspace crate relationships\n    73→flowchart TB\n    74→    user([User]):::startEnd\n    75→    cli(ezpdf-cli<br/>binary):::process\n    76→    app(ezpdf-app<br/>Tauri v2 + Svelte — v2):::process\n    77→    core(ezpdf-core<br/>library):::success\n    78→    lopdf(lopdf crate<br/>PDF object model):::process\n    79→    output([output.pdf]):::startEnd\n    80→\n    81→    user --> cli\n    82→    user --> app\n    83→    cli --> core\n    84→    app --> core\n    85→    core --> lopdf\n    86→    lopdf --> output\n    87→\n    88→    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    89→    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    90→    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    91→    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    92→    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    93→```\n    94→\n    95→### Command Execution Flow\n    96→\n    97→Every command follows the same path: CLI parses args → routes to core function → lossless PDF manipulation → file written.\n    98→\n    99→```mermaid\n   100→%% Command flow: CLI to core to output\n   101→flowchart LR\n   102→    A([ezpdf command]):::startEnd\n   103→    B(clap parses args):::process\n   104→    C{command?}:::decision\n   105→    D(merge.rs):::process\n   106→    E(split.rs):::process\n   107→    F(remove.rs):::process\n   108→    G(rotate.rs):::process\n   109→    H(reorder.rs):::process\n   110→    I(ezpdf-core):::success\n   111→    J(lopdf — object level edit):::process\n   112→    K{encrypted?}:::decision\n   113→    L(EzPdfError — suggest qpdf):::error\n   114→    M([output.pdf]):::startEnd\n   115→\n   116→    A --> B --> C\n   117→    C -->|merge| D\n   118→    C -->|split| E\n   119→    C -->|remove| F\n   120→    C -->|rotate| G\n   121→    C -->|reorder| H\n   122→    D & E & F & G & H --> I\n   123→    I --> K\n   124→    K -->|no| J\n   125→    K -->|yes| L\n   126→    J --> M\n   127→\n   128→    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   129→    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   130→    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   131→    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   132→    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   133→```\n   134→\n   135→### Lossless Quality Guarantee\n   136→\n   137→`ezpdf` never re-renders pages. It works at the PDF object level — moving page dictionaries and their referenced content streams around without ever decoding them.\n   138→\n   139→```mermaid\n   140→%% Lossless approach: what ezpdf does vs what it avoids\n   141→flowchart LR\n   142→    A([input.pdf]):::startEnd\n   143→    B(load PDF object graph):::process\n   144→    C{operation}:::decision\n   145→    D(copy page object refs):::success\n   146→    E(edit page dictionary):::success\n   147→    F(reorder Kids array):::success\n   148→    G(NEVER decode content streams):::error\n   149→    H(NEVER re-encode images):::error\n   150→    I(write modified object graph):::process\n   151→    J([output.pdf — same quality]):::startEnd\n   152→\n   153→    A --> B --> C\n   154→    C -->|merge/split/remove| D\n   155→    C -->|rotate| E\n   156→    C -->|reorder| F\n   157→    D & E & F --> I\n   158→    G -.->|avoided| I\n   159→    H -.->|avoided| I\n   160→    I --> J\n   161→\n   162→    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   163→    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   164→    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   165→    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   166→    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n   167→```\n   168→\n   169→---\n   170→\n   171→## Project Structure\n   172→\n   173→```\n   174→ez-pdf/\n   175→├── ezpdf-core/               # Library — all PDF logic\n   176→│   ├── src/\n   177→│   │   ├── lib.rs\n   178→│   │   ├── merge.rs\n   179→│   │   ├── split.rs\n   180→│   │   ├── remove.rs\n   181→│   │   ├── rotate.rs\n   182→│   │   ├── reorder.rs\n   183→│   │   ├── page_range.rs     # \"1-5,7,9-12\" parser\n   184→│   │   └── error.rs\n   185→│   └── tests/\n   186→│       └── fixtures/         # sample PDFs for integration tests\n   187→├── ezpdf-cli/                # Binary — CLI (clap)\n   188→│   └── src/\n   189→│       ├── main.rs\n   190→│       └── commands/\n   191→├── ezpdf-app/                # Desktop app — Tauri v2 + Svelte (v2)\n   192→├── benches/                  # criterion benchmarks\n   193→├── docs/\n   194→│   ├── brainstorms/          # design decisions\n   195→│   └── plans/                # implementation plan\n   196→├── task_plan.md              # TDD task list (ralph loop)\n   197→├── PROMPT.md                 # autonomous loop prompt\n   198→└── ralph-loop.sh             # autonomous implementation loop\n   199→```\n   200→\n   201→---\n   202→\n   203→## Development\n   204→\n   205→### Prerequisites\n   206→\n   207→```bash\n   208→# Rust (stable)\n   209→curl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh\n   210→\n   211→# Build & test\n   212→cargo build --workspace\n   213→cargo test --workspace\n   214→cargo clippy --workspace -- -D warnings\n   215→```\n   216→\n   217→### Autonomous Implementation (Ralph Loop)\n   218→\n   219→This project uses a [Ralph Loop](https://github.com/zhou-en/ez-pdf/blob/main/ralph-loop.sh) for autonomous TDD-driven implementation. Each task in `task_plan.md` follows a strict `[RED] → [GREEN] → [REFACTOR]` cycle.\n   220→\n   221→```bash\n   222→# Start the loop (runs until all tasks complete)\n   223→./ralph-loop.sh\n   224→\n   225→# Monitor progress in separate panes\n   226→tail -f ralph-loop.log\n   227→watch -n 5 git log --oneline -10\n   228→```\n   229→\n   230→The loop stops automatically when a blocker is found, or outputs `EZPDF V1 COMPLETE` when all 10 phases are done.\n   231→\n   232→---\n   233→\n   234→## Roadmap\n   235→\n   236→| Version | Scope |\n   237→|---------|-------|\n   238→| **v1.0** | merge, split, remove, rotate, reorder — CLI + Homebrew |\n   239→| **v1.1** | batch operations, `ezpdf info` command |\n   240→| **v2.0** | desktop app (Tauri v2 + Svelte), encrypted PDF support |\n   241→\n   242→---\n   243→\n   244→## License\n   245→\n   246→MIT\n   247→\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8b32962c-f496-4079-9ef0-4b12af617e35","uuid":"7466f7f4-4cc9-4e6d-984f-941f82b4c5f3","tool_use_result":{"type":"text","file":{"filePath":"/Users/enzhou/Projects/ez-pdf/README.md","content":"# ezpdf\n\nA fast, lossless PDF manipulation CLI tool written in Rust. Merge, split, remove, rotate, and reorder pages without ever re-encoding content — what goes in comes out at exactly the same quality.\n\nBuilt as a modern replacement for `pdftk`, with a developer-first experience: clean subcommands, intuitive flags, shell completions, and man pages.\n\n---\n\n## Features\n\n| Command    | Description                                          |\n|------------|------------------------------------------------------|\n| `merge`    | Combine two or more PDFs into one                    |\n| `split`    | Extract a page range or burst into individual pages  |\n| `remove`   | Delete specific pages or ranges                      |\n| `rotate`   | Rotate all or specific pages by 90/180/270°          |\n| `reorder`  | Rearrange pages by specifying a new order            |\n\n---\n\n## Installation\n\n```bash\n# Homebrew (macOS / Linux)\nbrew install zhou-en/tap/ezpdf\n\n# Cargo\ncargo install ezpdf\n```\n\n---\n\n## Usage\n\n```bash\n# Merge PDFs\nezpdf merge a.pdf b.pdf c.pdf -o combined.pdf\n\n# Split — extract a range\nezpdf split report.pdf 1-10 -o part1.pdf\n\n# Split — burst into individual pages\nezpdf split report.pdf --each -o ./pages/\n\n# Remove pages\nezpdf remove report.pdf 3,5,7-9 -o cleaned.pdf\n\n# Rotate all pages\nezpdf rotate report.pdf 90 -o rotated.pdf\n\n# Rotate specific pages\nezpdf rotate report.pdf 90 --pages 1,3,5 -o rotated.pdf\n\n# Reorder pages\nezpdf reorder report.pdf 3,1,2,4 -o reordered.pdf\n\n# Shell completions\nezpdf completions zsh >> ~/.zshrc\n```\n\nPage ranges use `1-5,7,9-12` syntax consistently across all commands. Pages are 1-indexed.\n\n---\n\n## Architecture\n\n### Workspace Structure\n\n`ezpdf` is a Cargo workspace with a shared core library. All PDF logic lives in `ezpdf-core` — the CLI and the future desktop app are thin shells over it.\n\n```mermaid\n%% Architecture: Cargo workspace crate relationships\nflowchart TB\n    user([User]):::startEnd\n    cli(ezpdf-cli<br/>binary):::process\n    app(ezpdf-app<br/>Tauri v2 + Svelte — v2):::process\n    core(ezpdf-core<br/>library):::success\n    lopdf(lopdf crate<br/>PDF object model):::process\n    output([output.pdf]):::startEnd\n\n    user --> cli\n    user --> app\n    cli --> core\n    app --> core\n    core --> lopdf\n    lopdf --> output\n\n    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n```\n\n### Command Execution Flow\n\nEvery command follows the same path: CLI parses args → routes to core function → lossless PDF manipulation → file written.\n\n```mermaid\n%% Command flow: CLI to core to output\nflowchart LR\n    A([ezpdf command]):::startEnd\n    B(clap parses args):::process\n    C{command?}:::decision\n    D(merge.rs):::process\n    E(split.rs):::process\n    F(remove.rs):::process\n    G(rotate.rs):::process\n    H(reorder.rs):::process\n    I(ezpdf-core):::success\n    J(lopdf — object level edit):::process\n    K{encrypted?}:::decision\n    L(EzPdfError — suggest qpdf):::error\n    M([output.pdf]):::startEnd\n\n    A --> B --> C\n    C -->|merge| D\n    C -->|split| E\n    C -->|remove| F\n    C -->|rotate| G\n    C -->|reorder| H\n    D & E & F & G & H --> I\n    I --> K\n    K -->|no| J\n    K -->|yes| L\n    J --> M\n\n    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n```\n\n### Lossless Quality Guarantee\n\n`ezpdf` never re-renders pages. It works at the PDF object level — moving page dictionaries and their referenced content streams around without ever decoding them.\n\n```mermaid\n%% Lossless approach: what ezpdf does vs what it avoids\nflowchart LR\n    A([input.pdf]):::startEnd\n    B(load PDF object graph):::process\n    C{operation}:::decision\n    D(copy page object refs):::success\n    E(edit page dictionary):::success\n    F(reorder Kids array):::success\n    G(NEVER decode content streams):::error\n    H(NEVER re-encode images):::error\n    I(write modified object graph):::process\n    J([output.pdf — same quality]):::startEnd\n\n    A --> B --> C\n    C -->|merge/split/remove| D\n    C -->|rotate| E\n    C -->|reorder| F\n    D & E & F --> I\n    G -.->|avoided| I\n    H -.->|avoided| I\n    I --> J\n\n    classDef startEnd fill:#e8d4f0,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef process fill:#e8f4fd,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef decision fill:#fff5e6,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef error fill:#fde8e8,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n    classDef success fill:#e8f5e9,stroke:#333,stroke-width:2px,color:#333\n```\n\n---\n\n## Project Structure\n\n```\nez-pdf/\n├── ezpdf-core/               # Library — all PDF logic\n│   ├── src/\n│   │   ├── lib.rs\n│   │   ├── merge.rs\n│   │   ├── split.rs\n│   │   ├── remove.rs\n│   │   ├── rotate.rs\n│   │   ├── reorder.rs\n│   │   ├── page_range.rs     # \"1-5,7,9-12\" parser\n│   │   └── error.rs\n│   └── tests/\n│       └── fixtures/         # sample PDFs for integration tests\n├── ezpdf-cli/                # Binary — CLI (clap)\n│   └── src/\n│       ├── main.rs\n│       └── commands/\n├── ezpdf-app/                # Desktop app — Tauri v2 + Svelte (v2)\n├── benches/                  # criterion benchmarks\n├── docs/\n│   ├── brainstorms/          # design decisions\n│   └── plans/                # implementation plan\n├── task_plan.md              # TDD task list (ralph loop)\n├── PROMPT.md                 # autonomous loop prompt\n└── ralph-loop.sh             # autonomous implementation loop\n```\n\n---\n\n## Development\n\n### Prerequisites\n\n```bash\n# Rust (stable)\ncurl --proto '=https' --tlsv1.2 -sSf https://sh.rustup.rs | sh\n\n# Build & test\ncargo build --workspace\ncargo test --workspace\ncargo clippy --workspace -- -D warnings\n```\n\n### Autonomous Implementation (Ralph Loop)\n\nThis project uses a [Ralph Loop](https://github.com/zhou-en/ez-pdf/blob/main/ralph-loop.sh) for autonomous TDD-driven implementation. Each task in `task_plan.md` follows a strict `[RED] → [GREEN] → [REFACTOR]` cycle.\n\n```bash\n# Start the loop (runs until all tasks complete)\n./ralph-loop.sh\n\n# Monitor progress in separate panes\ntail -f ralph-loop.log\nwatch -n 5 git log --oneline -10\n```\n\nThe loop stops automatically when a blocker is found, or outputs `EZPDF V1 COMPLETE` when all 10 phases are done.\n\n---\n\n## Roadmap\n\n| Version | Scope |\n|---------|-------|\n| **v1.0** | merge, split, remove, rotate, reorder — CLI + Homebrew |\n| **v1.1** | batch operations, `ezpdf info` command |\n| **v2.0** | desktop app (Tauri v2 + Svelte), encrypted PDF support |\n\n---\n\n## License\n\nMIT\n","numLines":247,"startLine":1,"totalLines":247}}}
