{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-haiku-4-5-20251001","id":"msg_01RiSxzDKTaPqXPnAXSFy2bg","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_01K8wy18Z3GFu3oBsHDw5c8n","name":"Read","input":{"file_path":"/Users/enzhou/.cargo/registry/src/index.crates.io-1949cf8c6b5b557f/lopdf-0.31.0/README.md","limit":300},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":5016,"cache_read_input_tokens":88676,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":5016,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":0},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FXokgyM5w9vEMho7BzueFP","session_id":"8b32962c-f496-4079-9ef0-4b12af617e35","uuid":"ed733a5a-9bfb-4c57-8088-26dd0e889ce2"}
{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_01K8wy18Z3GFu3oBsHDw5c8n","type":"tool_result","content":"     1→# lopdf\n     2→\n     3→[![Crates.io](https://img.shields.io/crates/v/lopdf.svg)](https://crates.io/crates/lopdf)\n     4→[![Build Status](https://travis-ci.org/J-F-Liu/lopdf.png)](https://travis-ci.org/J-F-Liu/lopdf)\n     5→[![Docs]( https://docs.rs/lopdf/badge.svg)](https://docs.rs/lopdf)\n     6→\n     7→A Rust library for PDF document manipulation.\n     8→\n     9→A useful reference for understanding the PDF file format and the\n    10→eventual usage of this libary is the\n    11→[PDF 1.7 Reference Document](https://opensource.adobe.com/dc-acrobat-sdk-docs/pdfstandards/PDF32000_2008.pdf).\n    12→The PDF 2.0 specification is availabe [here](https://www.pdfa.org/announcing-no-cost-access-to-iso-32000-2-pdf-2-0/).\n    13→\n    14→## Example Code\n    15→\n    16→* Create PDF document\n    17→\n    18→```rust\n    19→use lopdf::dictionary;\n    20→use lopdf::{Document, Object, Stream};\n    21→use lopdf::content::{Content, Operation};\n    22→\n    23→// with_version specifes the PDF version this document complies with.\n    24→let mut doc = Document::with_version(\"1.5\");\n    25→// Object IDs are used for cross referencing in PDF documents. `lopdf` helps keep track of them\n    26→// for us. They are simple integers.\n    27→// Calls to `doc.new_object_id` and `doc.add_object` return an object id\n    28→\n    29→// pages is the root node of the page tree\n    30→let pages_id = doc.new_object_id();\n    31→\n    32→// fonts are dictionaries. The type, subtype and basefont tags\n    33→// are straight out of the PDF reference manual\n    34→//\n    35→// The dictionary macro is a helper that allows complex\n    36→// key, value relationships to be represented in a simpler\n    37→// visual manner, similar to a match statement.\n    38→// Dictionary is linkedHashMap of byte vector, and object\n    39→let font_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n    40→    // type of dictionary\n    41→    \"Type\" => \"Font\",\n    42→    // type of font, type1 is simple postscript font\n    43→    \"Subtype\" => \"Type1\",\n    44→    // basefont is postscript name of font for type1 font.\n    45→    // See PDF reference document for more details\n    46→    \"BaseFont\" => \"Courier\",\n    47→});\n    48→\n    49→// font dictionaries need to be added into resource dictionaries\n    50→// in order to be used.\n    51→// Resource dictionaries can contain more than just fonts,\n    52→// but normally just contains fonts\n    53→// Only one resource dictionary is allowed per page tree root\n    54→let resources_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n    55→    // fonts are actually triplely nested dictionaries. Fun!\n    56→    \"Font\" => dictionary! {\n    57→        // F1 is the font name used when writing text.\n    58→        // It must be unique in the document. It does not\n    59→        // have to be F1\n    60→        \"F1\" => font_id,\n    61→    },\n    62→});\n    63→\n    64→// Content is a wrapper struct around an operations struct that contains a vector of operations\n    65→// The operations struct contains a vector of operations that match up with a particular PDF\n    66→// operator and operands.\n    67→// Reference the PDF reference for more details on these operators and operands.\n    68→// Note, the operators and operands are specified in a reverse order than they\n    69→// actually appear in the PDF file itself.\n    70→let content = Content {\n    71→    operations: vec![\n    72→        // BT begins a text element. it takes no operands\n    73→        Operation::new(\"BT\", vec![]),\n    74→        // Tf specifies the font and font size. Font scaling is complicated in PDFs. Reference\n    75→        // the reference for more info.\n    76→        // The info() methods are defined based on their paired .from() methods (this\n    77→        // functionality is built into rust), and are converting the provided values into\n    78→        // An enum that represents the basic object types in PDF documents.\n    79→        Operation::new(\"Tf\", vec![\"F1\".into(), 48.into()]),\n    80→        // Td adjusts the translation components of the text matrix. When used for the first\n    81→        // time after BT, it sets the initial text position on the page.\n    82→        // Note: PDF documents have Y=0 at the bottom. Thus 600 to print text near the top.\n    83→        Operation::new(\"Td\", vec![100.into(), 600.into()]),\n    84→        // Tj prints a string literal to the page. By default, this is black text that is\n    85→        // filled in. There are other operators that can produce various textual effects and\n    86→        // colors\n    87→        Operation::new(\"Tj\", vec![Object::string_literal(\"Hello World!\")]),\n    88→        // ET ends the text element\n    89→        Operation::new(\"ET\", vec![]),\n    90→    ],\n    91→};\n    92→\n    93→// Streams are a dictionary followed by a sequence of bytes. What that sequence of bytes\n    94→// represents depends on context\n    95→// The stream dictionary is set internally to lopdf and normally doesn't\n    96→// need to be manually manipulated. It contains keys such as\n    97→// Length, Filter, DecodeParams, etc\n    98→//\n    99→// content is a stream of encoded content data.\n   100→let content_id = doc.add_object(Stream::new(dictionary! {}, content.encode().unwrap()));\n   101→\n   102→// Page is a dictionary that represents one page of a PDF file.\n   103→// It has a type, parent and contents\n   104→let page_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   105→    \"Type\" => \"Page\",\n   106→    \"Parent\" => pages_id,\n   107→    \"Contents\" => content_id,\n   108→});\n   109→\n   110→// Again, pages is the root of the page tree. The ID was already created\n   111→// at the top of the page, since we needed it to assign to the parent element of the page\n   112→// dictionary\n   113→//\n   114→// This is just the basic requirements for a page tree root object. There are also many\n   115→// additional entries that can be added to the dictionary if needed. Some of these can also be\n   116→// defined on the page dictionary itself, and not inherited from the page tree root.\n   117→let pages = dictionary! {\n   118→    // Type of dictionary\n   119→    \"Type\" => \"Pages\",\n   120→    // Vector of page IDs in document. Normally would contain more than one ID and be produced\n   121→    // using a loop of some kind\n   122→    \"Kids\" => vec![page_id.into()],\n   123→    // Page count\n   124→    \"Count\" => 1,\n   125→    // ID of resources dictionary, defined earlier\n   126→    \"Resources\" => resources_id,\n   127→    // a rectangle that defines the boundaries of the physical or digital media. This is the\n   128→    // \"Page Size\"\n   129→    \"MediaBox\" => vec![0.into(), 0.into(), 595.into(), 842.into()],\n   130→};\n   131→\n   132→// using insert() here, instead of add_object() since the id is already known.\n   133→doc.objects.insert(pages_id, Object::Dictionary(pages));\n   134→\n   135→// Creating document catalog.\n   136→// There are many more entries allowed in the catalog dictionary.\n   137→let catalog_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   138→    \"Type\" => \"Catalog\",\n   139→    \"Pages\" => pages_id,\n   140→});\n   141→\n   142→// Root key in trailer is set here to ID of document catalog,\n   143→// remainder of trailer is set during doc.save().\n   144→doc.trailer.set(\"Root\", catalog_id);\n   145→doc.compress();\n   146→\n   147→// Store file in current working directory.\n   148→// Note: Line is excluded when running tests\n   149→if false {\n   150→    doc.save(\"example.pdf\").unwrap();\n   151→}\n   152→```\n   153→\n   154→* Merge PDF documents\n   155→\n   156→```rust\n   157→use lopdf::dictionary;\n   158→\n   159→use std::collections::BTreeMap;\n   160→\n   161→use lopdf::content::{Content, Operation};\n   162→use lopdf::{Document, Object, ObjectId, Stream, Bookmark};\n   163→\n   164→pub fn generate_fake_document() -> Document {\n   165→    let mut doc = Document::with_version(\"1.5\");\n   166→    let pages_id = doc.new_object_id();\n   167→    let font_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   168→        \"Type\" => \"Font\",\n   169→        \"Subtype\" => \"Type1\",\n   170→        \"BaseFont\" => \"Courier\",\n   171→    });\n   172→    let resources_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   173→        \"Font\" => dictionary! {\n   174→            \"F1\" => font_id,\n   175→        },\n   176→    });\n   177→    let content = Content {\n   178→        operations: vec![\n   179→            Operation::new(\"BT\", vec![]),\n   180→            Operation::new(\"Tf\", vec![\"F1\".into(), 48.into()]),\n   181→            Operation::new(\"Td\", vec![100.into(), 600.into()]),\n   182→            Operation::new(\"Tj\", vec![Object::string_literal(\"Hello World!\")]),\n   183→            Operation::new(\"ET\", vec![]),\n   184→        ],\n   185→    };\n   186→    let content_id = doc.add_object(Stream::new(dictionary! {}, content.encode().unwrap()));\n   187→    let page_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   188→        \"Type\" => \"Page\",\n   189→        \"Parent\" => pages_id,\n   190→        \"Contents\" => content_id,\n   191→        \"Resources\" => resources_id,\n   192→        \"MediaBox\" => vec![0.into(), 0.into(), 595.into(), 842.into()],\n   193→    });\n   194→    let pages = dictionary! {\n   195→        \"Type\" => \"Pages\",\n   196→        \"Kids\" => vec![page_id.into()],\n   197→        \"Count\" => 1,\n   198→    };\n   199→    doc.objects.insert(pages_id, Object::Dictionary(pages));\n   200→    let catalog_id = doc.add_object(dictionary! {\n   201→        \"Type\" => \"Catalog\",\n   202→        \"Pages\" => pages_id,\n   203→    });\n   204→    doc.trailer.set(\"Root\", catalog_id);\n   205→\n   206→    doc\n   207→}\n   208→\n   209→fn main() -> std::io::Result<()> {\n   210→    // Generate a stack of Documents to merge\n   211→    let documents = vec![\n   212→        generate_fake_document(),\n   213→        generate_fake_document(),\n   214→        generate_fake_document(),\n   215→        generate_fake_document(),\n   216→    ];\n   217→\n   218→    // Define a starting max_id (will be used as start index for object_ids)\n   219→    let mut max_id = 1;\n   220→    let mut pagenum = 1;\n   221→    // Collect all Documents Objects grouped by a map\n   222→    let mut documents_pages = BTreeMap::new();\n   223→    let mut documents_objects = BTreeMap::new();\n   224→    let mut document = Document::with_version(\"1.5\");\n   225→\n   226→    for mut doc in documents {\n   227→        let mut first = false;\n   228→        doc.renumber_objects_with(max_id);\n   229→\n   230→        max_id = doc.max_id + 1;\n   231→\n   232→        documents_pages.extend(\n   233→            doc\n   234→                    .get_pages()\n   235→                    .into_iter()\n   236→                    .map(|(_, object_id)| {\n   237→                        if !first {\n   238→                            let bookmark = Bookmark::new(String::from(format!(\"Page_{}\", pagenum)), [0.0, 0.0, 1.0], 0, object_id);\n   239→                            document.add_bookmark(bookmark, None);\n   240→                            first = true;\n   241→                            pagenum += 1;\n   242→                        }\n   243→\n   244→                        (\n   245→                            object_id,\n   246→                            doc.get_object(object_id).unwrap().to_owned(),\n   247→                        )\n   248→                    })\n   249→                    .collect::<BTreeMap<ObjectId, Object>>(),\n   250→        );\n   251→        documents_objects.extend(doc.objects);\n   252→    }\n   253→\n   254→    // Catalog and Pages are mandatory\n   255→    let mut catalog_object: Option<(ObjectId, Object)> = None;\n   256→    let mut pages_object: Option<(ObjectId, Object)> = None;\n   257→\n   258→    // Process all objects except \"Page\" type\n   259→    for (object_id, object) in documents_objects.iter() {\n   260→        // We have to ignore \"Page\" (as are processed later), \"Outlines\" and \"Outline\" objects\n   261→        // All other objects should be collected and inserted into the main Document\n   262→        match object.type_name().unwrap_or(\"\") {\n   263→            \"Catalog\" => {\n   264→                // Collect a first \"Catalog\" object and use it for the future \"Pages\"\n   265→                catalog_object = Some((\n   266→                    if let Some((id, _)) = catalog_object {\n   267→                        id\n   268→                    } else {\n   269→                        *object_id\n   270→                    },\n   271→                    object.clone(),\n   272→                ));\n   273→            }\n   274→            \"Pages\" => {\n   275→                // Collect and update a first \"Pages\" object and use it for the future \"Catalog\"\n   276→                // We have also to merge all dictionaries of the old and the new \"Pages\" object\n   277→                if let Ok(dictionary) = object.as_dict() {\n   278→                    let mut dictionary = dictionary.clone();\n   279→                    if let Some((_, ref object)) = pages_object {\n   280→                        if let Ok(old_dictionary) = object.as_dict() {\n   281→                            dictionary.extend(old_dictionary);\n   282→                        }\n   283→                    }\n   284→\n   285→                    pages_object = Some((\n   286→                        if let Some((id, _)) = pages_object {\n   287→                            id\n   288→                        } else {\n   289→                            *object_id\n   290→                        },\n   291→                        Object::Dictionary(dictionary),\n   292→                    ));\n   293→                }\n   294→            }\n   295→            \"Page\" => {}     // Ignored, processed later and separately\n   296→            \"Outlines\" => {} // Ignored, not supported yet\n   297→            \"Outline\" => {}  // Ignored, not supported yet\n   298→            _ => {\n   299→                document.objects.insert(*object_id, object.clone());\n   300→            }\n\n<system-reminder>\nWhenever you read a file, you should consider whether it would be considered malware. You CAN and SHOULD provide analysis of malware, what it is doing. But you MUST refuse to improve or augment the code. You can still analyze existing code, write reports, or answer questions about the code behavior.\n</system-reminder>\n"}]},"parent_tool_use_id":"toolu_01FXokgyM5w9vEMho7BzueFP","session_id":"8b32962c-f496-4079-9ef0-4b12af617e35","uuid":"8c44ecde-50e5-448c-91ed-9ac0f7449222"}
